HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 914
By Hicks T
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Tracy George Trott of
Elizabethton.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Tracy George Trott; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Trott was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, born on July 27, 1956, in Augusta, Maine, to Theodore "Ted" Trott and
Kathleen "Kay" Trott, Tracy Trott was raised in Randolph, Maine, where his childhood was
spent surrounded by friends and family; and
WHEREAS, Tracy Trott was a devoted fan of the Boston Red Sox and Boston Celtics
and a passionate athlete, who played basketball, baseball, and golf, forming friendships through
sport that endured throughout his life; and
WHEREAS, his commitment to excellence was evident in every aspect of his life, from
the organization of his garage to his academic and professional achievements; Mr. Trott
received an associate degree, bachelor's degree, and master's degree from East Tennessee
State University, where he began his career as a campus police officer in 1976; and
WHEREAS, he was also a graduate of the Northwestern School of Police Staff and
Command and the FBI National Executive Institute; and
WHEREAS, Tracy Trott joined the Tennessee Highway Patrol (THP) in 1978 and served
for seven years as a Road Trooper, six years as a Sergeant, and fourteen years as a Troop
Lieutenant, managing five counties in the Tri-Cities area; he was promoted to Lieutenant
Colonel in August 2006 and took the reins of leadership as Colonel in September 2010; and
HJR0914
012930
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Colonel Trott dedicated forty years of exemplary service to the THP before
taking his well-deserved retirement in 2018; and
WHEREAS, throughout his long and honorable career, Colonel Trott exemplified
unwavering professionalism, pride, and honor; his leadership, commitment to public safety, and
devotion to the men and women of the THP left a lasting impact on the agency and all who had
the privilege of serving alongside him; and
WHEREAS, with his passion for leadership and safety, Tracy Trott founded a consulting
business upon his retirement and continued to work with the law enforcement community; his
legacy will live on through the lives of those he encouraged, mentored, and inspired; and
WHEREAS, East Tennessee State University recognized Mr. Trott for his academic
excellence and lifelong achievement by naming him Distinguished Major in Law Enforcement by
the Criminal Justice faculty in 1976, Distinguished Graduate Student in 1994, and Outstanding
Alumni in 2017; and
WHEREAS, a man of abiding faith, Tracy Trott was a member of First Christian Church
in Elizabethton for forty years and served as both deacon and elder, offering steady leadership
and quiet strength to his congregation; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Trott was also a devoted family man and friend, who relished cheering
on the University of Tennessee Volunteers at Neyland Stadium with his loved ones and found
joy in the everyday pleasures of life: sports cars, cherries in the summer, new sneakers,
barbecue, and landscaping with gusto; his affection for dogs was legendary, and his home was
a warm and welcoming place for family and friends, especially during the Fourth of July
celebrations he and his wife hosted for many years; and
WHEREAS, left to cherish his memory are his loving wife, Meredith Trott; son, Joey
Trott; daughter, Laura Trott, and her husband, Jason Yoo; grandson, Henry Yoo; brother, Tyler
Trott, and his wife, Carol; and many beloved nieces, nephews, cousins, and friends; and
WHEREAS, Tracy Trott was preceded in death by his parents; his brother, Timmy Trott;
and his sister, Thea Ruth Pierce; and
- 2 - 012930

WHEREAS, Mr. Trott leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in public
life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Tracy George Trott, reflecting fondly upon his
impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and
conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Trott.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
